@module checker
@lang aria
@aid_version 0.2
@layer 2
@purpose Type checking, trait resolution, generics, and effect verification for the Aria self-hosting compiler. Implements a three-pass architecture over a DeclIndex: (1) register types, (2) register function signatures, (3) check bodies. Uses an immutable-update pattern where every mutation returns a new Checker struct.
@depends [lexer, parser, resolver, diagnostic]
@workflow Runs after parsing and resolution. Receives tokens, DeclIndex, NodePool, and SymbolTable from earlier passes. Produces CheckResult containing TypeStore, TypeRegistry, TraitRegistry, and diagnostics for the lowerer/codegen stages.

---

@type TypeKind
@kind sum
@variants
  TyI8 — 8-bit signed integer
  TyI16 — 16-bit signed integer
  TyI32 — 32-bit signed integer
  TyI64 — 64-bit signed integer
  TyU8 — 8-bit unsigned integer
  TyU16 — 16-bit unsigned integer
  TyU32 — 32-bit unsigned integer
  TyU64 — 64-bit unsigned integer
  TyF32 — 32-bit float
  TyF64 — 64-bit float
  TyBool — Boolean
  TyStr — String
  TyChar — Character
  TyUnit — Unit type ()
  TyArray — Array type [T]
  TyFunction — Function type fn(A) -> B
  TyNamed — Named/user-defined type
  TyResult — Result type T ! E
  TyOptional — Optional type T?
  TyTypeVar — Generic type variable
  TyTraitObject — Trait object
  TyTuple — Tuple type
  TyNever — Never type (diverges)
  TyUnknown — Unknown / unresolved
  TyNone — Sentinel
@purpose Classifies every type in the system. Primitives have dedicated variants; compound types (Array, Function, Result, Optional, Tuple) store sub-type references via TypeInfo fields. TyNone is the sentinel for invalid/missing types at index 0. TyUnknown is used for graceful error recovery when a type cannot be resolved.
@invariants TyNone only appears at TypeStore index 0. TyNever is assignable to any type (used for diverging expressions like return/panic). TyUnknown is treated as compatible with any type to prevent cascading errors.
@source_file src/checker/types.aria
@source_line 14

---

@type TypeInfo
@kind struct
@fields
  kind: TypeKind — Type classification
  name: str — Type name (for named types, type vars); comma-delimited type IDs for tuples
  type_id: i64 — Primary associated type ID (element type for arrays, ok type for results, return for functions, inner for optionals)
  type_id2: i64 — Secondary associated type ID (error type for results only)
  param_start: i64 — Start index for function parameter types in the TypeStore
  param_count: i64 — Number of function parameters; also tuple arity for TyTuple
@purpose Flat representation of a type, avoiding recursive type definitions. All compound types encode their sub-types as integer IDs referencing other TypeStore entries. This design enables the bootstrap compiler to handle the type system without needing recursive data structures.
@invariants For TyArray: type_id = element type ID. For TyResult: type_id = ok type, type_id2 = error type. For TyOptional: type_id = inner type. For TyTuple: name = comma-delimited type ID string, param_count = arity. For TyFunction: type_id = return type, param_start/param_count index into parameter list.
@notes Tuples encode element type IDs as a comma-delimited string in the name field (e.g., "1,12,11") because the bootstrap compiler cannot handle recursive/variable-length type representations. This is parsed by _parse_int_from at access time. [src: types.aria:114]
@source_file src/checker/types.aria
@source_line 74

---

@type TypeStore
@kind struct
@fields
  types: [TypeInfo] — All registered types
@purpose Central type repository. Types are identified by their index (i64 ID) in this array. Well-known primitives occupy fixed indices 0-20, user-defined types start at index 21.
@invariants Index 0 is always TyNone sentinel. Indices 1-14 are primitives (i64, i32, i16, i8, u64, u32, u16, u8, f64, f32, bool, str, char, unit). Index 15 = Never, 16 = Unknown, 17-20 = reserved concurrency types (Chan, Task, ChanSend, ChanRecv). Types are append-only; IDs are stable once assigned.
@antipatterns Never access store.types directly by index without bounds checking; use store_get which returns the sentinel for out-of-range IDs.
@source_file src/checker/types.aria
@source_line 119

---

@type FieldInfo
@kind struct
@fields
  name: str — Field name
  type_id: i64 — Field type ID
@purpose Represents a single field in a struct or sum type variant. Used in StructDef.fields and variant field arrays.
@invariants Index 0 in any FieldInfo array is a sentinel with name="" and type_id=0.
@source_file src/checker/types.aria
@source_line 395

---

@type StructDef
@kind struct
@fields
  name: str — Struct or sum type name
  fields: [FieldInfo] — Struct fields (1-based; index 0 is sentinel)
  is_sum: bool — Whether this is a sum type
  variant_names: [str] — Sum type variant names (1-based; index 0 is sentinel)
  variant_field_counts: [i64] — Fields per variant (1-based)
  variant_field_names: [str] — Flat list of all variant field names
  variant_field_types: [i64] — Flat list of all variant field type IDs
  variant_field_offsets: [i64] — Start offset per variant into flat field lists
  generic_count: i64 — Number of generic parameters (0-3)
  generic_name_0: str — First generic parameter name
  generic_name_1: str — Second generic parameter name
  generic_name_2: str — Third generic parameter name
@purpose Unified representation for structs, sum types, newtypes, and generic struct definitions. Sum type variant data uses a flat encoding scheme to avoid nested arrays (which the bootstrap compiler cannot handle).
@invariants All arrays are 1-based with sentinel at index 0. For sum types: variant_field_offsets[i] points into variant_field_names/variant_field_types for variant i's fields. generic_count is capped at 3. For plain structs, variant_names has only the sentinel.
@notes The flat encoding of variant fields (counts/names/types/offsets as parallel arrays) is a design constraint from the bootstrap compiler's lack of support for arrays-of-arrays. [src: types.aria:404]
@source_file src/checker/types.aria
@source_line 404

---

@type FnSig
@kind struct
@fields
  name: str — Function name
  param_names: [str] — Parameter names (1-based; index 0 is sentinel)
  param_types: [i64] — Parameter type IDs (1-based; index 0 is sentinel 0)
  return_type: i64 — Return type ID
  error_type: i64 — Error type ID (0 = no error, function is infallible)
  generic_count: i64 — Number of generic params (0-3)
  generic_name_0: str — First generic name
  generic_name_1: str — Second generic name
  generic_name_2: str — Third generic name
  generic_bound_0: str — First generic trait bound (supports multi-bounds: "Eq+Hash")
  generic_bound_1: str — Second generic trait bound
  generic_bound_2: str — Third generic trait bound
  token_start: i64 — Token position of declaration (for generic body re-checking)
  has_io: bool — Has IO effect
  has_fs: bool — Has FS effect
  has_net: bool — Has Net effect
  has_ffi: bool — Has FFI effect
  has_async: bool — Has Async effect
@purpose Stores the complete signature of a function including parameter types, return/error types, generic parameters with trait bounds, and declared effects. Used for call-site type checking, generic monomorphization, and effect verification.
@invariants param_names and param_types are parallel arrays, both 1-based. generic_count capped at 3. Trait bounds use "+" as separator for multi-bounds (e.g., "Eq+Hash+Clone"). error_type=0 means the function cannot fail.
@notes Effect flags use boolean fields rather than an array because the bootstrap compiler has simpler codegen for booleans. Fs implies Io, Net implies Io (checked by fn_has_effect). [src: types.aria:557]
@source_file src/checker/types.aria
@source_line 513

